revision.text:
'''Amplitude of Low Frequency Fluctuations''' ('''ALFF''') and '''fractional Amplitude of Low Frequency Fluctuations''' ('''f/ALFF''') are [[neuroimaging]] methods used to measure spontaneous fluctuations in [[Blood-oxygen-level dependent|BOLD-fMRI]] signal intensity for a given region in the [[resting state fMRI|resting brain]]. Whole-brain ALFF shows greater signal in [[posterior cingulate cortex|posterior cingulate]], [[precuneus]], and [[medial prefrontal cortex|medial prefrontal]] areas of the [[default mode network]],<ref name=Zang2007>{{Cite journal | pmid = 16919409 | date = 2007 | author1 = Zang | first1 = Y. F. | title = Altered baseline brain activity in children with ADHD revealed by resting-state functional MRI | journal = Brain and Development | volume = 29 | issue = 2 | pages = 83–91 | last2 = He | first2 = Y | last3 = Zhu | first3 = C. Z. | last4 = Cao | first4 = Q. J. | last5 = Sui | first5 = M. Q. | last6 = Liang | first6 = M | last7 = Tian | first7 = L. X. | last8 = Jiang | first8 = T. Z. | last9 = Wang | first9 = Y. F. | doi = 10.1016/j.braindev.2006.07.002 }}</ref> but also in non-cortical areas near the [[Ventricular system|ventricles]], [[Cistern (neuroanatomy)|cisterns]] and large blood vessels. f/ALFF reduces the sensitivity of ALFF to physiological noise by taking the ratio of each frequency (0.01-0.08&nbsp;Hz) to the total frequency range (0-0.25&nbsp;Hz).<ref name=Zuo2008>{{Cite journal | pmid = 3902859 | date = 1985 | author1 = Wallis | first1 = I | title = Immunolocalization of a neuronal growth-dependent membrane glycoprotein | journal = The Journal of Cell Biology | volume = 101 | issue = 5 Pt 1 | pages = 1990–8 | last2 = Ellis | first2 = L | last3 = Suh | first3 = K | last4 = Pfenninger | first4 = K. H. | pmc = 2113966 | doi = 10.1083/jcb.101.5.1990 }}</ref> Both measures have been investigated as part of reliable<ref>{{Cite journal | pmid = 2856476 | date = 1988 | author1 = Tachibana | first1 = M | title = Retinal bipolar cells receive negative feedback input from GABAergic amacrine cells | journal = Visual neuroscience | volume = 1 | issue = 3 | pages = 297–305 | last2 = Kaneko | first2 = A }}</ref> biomarkers for many neurological conditions including [[schizophrenia]],<ref>{{Cite journal |pmid = 2822110|date = 1987|last1 = Böhme|first1 = R|title = A high-affinity plasma membrane Ca2+-ATPase in Dictyostelium discoideum: Its relation to cAMP-induced Ca2+ fluxes|journal = Biochimica et Biophysica Acta|volume = 904|issue = 1|pages = 125–30|first2 = J|last2=Bumann|last3 = Aeckerle|first3 = S|last4 = Malchow|first4 = D|doi = 10.1016/0005-2736(87)90093-9}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | pmid = 3737471 | date = 1986 | author1 = Kayser | first1 = K | title = Neighborhood analysis of low magnification structures (glands) in healthy, adenomatous, and carcinomatous colon mucosa | journal = Pathology, research and practice | volume = 181 | issue = 2 | pages = 153–8 | last2 = Shaver | first2 = M | last3 = Modlinger | first3 = F | last4 = Postl | first4 = K | last5 = Moyers | first5 = J. J. }}</ref> and [[ADHD]].<ref name="Zang2007" />
